  "summary": "After Megan Bard denies a statement, Poirot asks Mary Deauville if she has a boyfriend, which causes her visible discomfort. Poirot then decides to depart for Eastbourne with Hastings. While traveling along the coast road from Pevensey, they stop to visit Pevensey Castle. Nearby, Hastings observes a group of young girls singing a song about catching a fox and putting it in a cage. Poirot finds the lyrics \"terrible,\" comparing the idea of a fox being caged to the \"quick and cruel death\" of a fox hunt.\n\nPoirot decides to forgo the trip to Eastbourne to meet privately with Alexander Bonaparte Castor, using a Home Office license obtained through police connections. During their meeting, Castor appears nervous and hunched. When Poirot identifies himself as the recipient of the letters Castor allegedly wrote, Castor denies authorship, claiming a \"grand conspiracy\" is being orchestrated against him by his enemies.\n\nCastor discusses his life, noting that his ambitious mother gave him his name and that he has always felt inadequate and timid. He mentions that he enjoyed the equality of the war but suffered a head injury that caused occasional lapses in memory or behavior. He describes his struggle to survive the Great Depression by working as a clerk and later selling stockings. When Poirot suggests that the company denies his claims, Castor insists he has typed letters as evidence. Poirot then reveals that the letters were typed on a specific typewriter—the one found in Castor's own room.",
